Open a shell in the container:

docker exec -it <container_name_or_id> bash
# or sh, depending on the image

(e.g., docker exec -it db_container bash)

Connect to the PostgreSQL database:
Once inside the container's shell, run the psql command with your credentials. You may need to switch to the postgres user first.
bash
# (Optional) Switch user if necessary
su postgres 

# Connect to the database
psql -U <username> -d <database_name>

(e.g., psql -U myuser -d mydatabase)
Run SQL statements:
You are now in the psql prompt (e.g., mydatabase=>). You can run SQL commands (which must end with a semicolon ;) or special psql meta-commands (which start with a backslash \).
List all databases: \l
Connect to a different database: \c <database_name>
List tables: \dt
Run a SQL query: SELECT * FROM my_table;
Exit the psql shell and container:
To exit the psql prompt: Type \q and press Enter.
To exit the container's shell and return to your host terminal: Type exit and press Enter.

Method 2: Run a Single SQL Command Directly
You can execute a single SQL command without entering the interactive shell using the -c flag with psql. 
bash
docker exec -it <container_name_or_id> psql -U <username> -d <database_name> -c "YOUR SQL COMMAND;"

(e.g., docker exec -it db_container psql -U myuser -d mydatabase -c "SELECT * FROM users;")
